<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-233-710  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 233 710.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  March 12 1990 v7 n11 p13(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>LECs step up use of fiber as long haulers scale back; FCC studyfocuses on 1989 installation efforts. (local carriers; FederalCommunications Committee)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taff, Anita.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>According to a study issued by the Federal CommunicationsCommission, long distance carriers significantly reduced theamount of fiber-optic cable installed in networks, laying half asmany miles of fiber as they did in 1988, while local carriersincreased their use of fiber-optic cable.andP;  Long-distance carriersfocused more on optimizing previously deployed fiber, equipping itwith necessary electronics ready for service, and upgradingexisting fiber with new technologies.andP;  On the other hand, localregional Bell holding companies collectively increased the numberof fiber miles by 30 percent, much of the increase seen in thesubscriber loop.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionReportsFiber OpticsGrowthTelecommunicationsCables.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>